	id="corpus-precedence-rules-visualization-fullscreen"></div>

<div class="accordion" id="accordion-read-embedded">
	<div class="accordion-group">
		<div class="accordion-heading">
			<a class="accordion-toggle" data-toggle="collapse"
				data-parent="#accordion-edit-embedded"
				href="#collapseGlosserSettingsEE"> <i class="icon-bar-chart"></i>
				<strong class="locale_Glosser_settings">Semi-automatic
					glossing and morpheme segmentation</strong>
			</a>
		</div>
		<div class="accordion-body collapse" id="collapseGlosserSettingsEE">
			<div class="accordion-inner">
				<span class="locale_glosser_explanation">You can use a
          glosser from any LingSync corpus, you need to have permission
          (ask them to add you as a reader on their corpus). For example, if
          you and your collaborators are working on Mi'gmaq, you might have a
          master corpus with the most data that you all can use to gloss your
          corpus. For an example url, see LingLlama's sample Quechua corpus:
          https://corpusdev.lingsync.org/lingllama-firstcorpus/_design/pages/_view/precedence_rules?group=true</span>
        <br /> <span>You can also create your own glosser web
          service or use an existing glosser/morpheme segmenter you have
          access too as long as it is available on a URL and uses a similar data schema. <a
          href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/viewform?formkey=dGFyREp4WmhBRURYNzFkcWZMTnpkV2c6MQ"
          target="_new">Contact us</a> if you would like more details.
        </span>
        <label>Glosser URL:</label>
				<p class="glosserURL"><strong>{{glosserURL}}</strong></p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

